<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A"><gtr:id>2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sch of Philosophy Psychology &amp; Language</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Old College</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>South Bridge</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Mayfield Road</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH8 9YL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A"><gtr:id>2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Old College</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>South Bridge</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Mayfield Road</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH8 9YL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/701C0C02-E2E7-493C-87DC-EF5E6C0FC4C0"><gtr:id>701C0C02-E2E7-493C-87DC-EF5E6C0FC4C0</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Florence</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Marguerite</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Bonacina</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH046119%2F1"><gtr:id>8314495E-8116-4627-8029-43A2ABB15C20</gtr:id><gtr:title>Language-in-education policy in migratory contexts</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H046119/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Traditionally language policy has been conceptualised as a notion separate from that of practice. This is specifically the case in language-in-education policy and classroom code-switching research where language practices are said to either reflect or challenge school language policies (eg Li Wei and Martin, 2009; Martin, 2005). &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Recently, however, Spolsky (2004, 2007) has argued that policy and practice need not be seen as distinct and that, in fact, there is policy within practices themselves (a &amp;quot;practiced language policy&amp;quot; in Bonacina, 2010). This conceptualisation of policy is a decisive development in the field of language policy research, but an embryonic one since no indication has yet been given as to how practiced language policies can be investigated. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The aim of this project is to address this methodological gap. Its main claim is that Conversation Analysis can be used to investigate practiced language policies. It adopts a case study methodology, investigating a practiced language-in-education policy in a migratory context: that of France's induction classrooms for newly-arrived immigrant children. Findings show that the practiced language-in-education policy in this particular context consists of a set of multilingual interactional norms classroom participants orient to when choosing a &amp;quot;medium of classroom interaction&amp;quot; (Bonacina and Gafaranga, 2010).&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-11-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-12-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>81272</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A17D18CD-33D2-4C88-85DE-AD0D615631A4</gtr:id><gtr:title>Categories and language choice in multilingual classrooms: the relevance of &amp;acirc;??teacher-hood&amp;acirc;??</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Language and Education</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1879325ac88d3d2e7eb3e09b7c2592c3"><gtr:id>1879325ac88d3d2e7eb3e09b7c2592c3</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bonacina-Pugh F</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:d